    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my spouse and children?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Yes, spouse and children can get Dependent visas. With regular work visa, spouse can work up to 28 hours/week. With HSP visa (70+ points), spouse can work full-time. Children are covered under your Shakai Hoken for medical care.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Japanese for the visa?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Japanese is not required for visa approval. However, it significantly helps with daily life, healthcare access, and career progression. JLPT N1 or N2 certification adds points for HSP visa and is valued by employers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if I lose my job?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">You have 3 months to find new employment in the same visa category before your status is at risk. Register at Hello Work (employment office) for job search support. You may qualify for unemployment benefits if you contributed for 12+ months.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I freelance or do side work?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Your work visa only permits work for your sponsoring employer. For side jobs, you need "Permission to Engage in Activity Other Than That Permitted" from immigration. This is usually granted for up to 28 hours/week of permitted activities.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until permanent residence?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Standard path: 10 years of continuous residence with 5+ years on work visa. HSP with 70+ points: 3 years. HSP with 80+ points: 1 year. You must demonstrate stable income, pay taxes, and have no criminal record. No Japanese language test required.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is maternity covered by Shakai Hoken?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Pregnancy checkups and normal delivery are not covered by health insurance (considered not "medical"). However, you receive a lump-sum birth allowance of ¥500,000 and can get maternity leave benefits (67% of salary). Complications during pregnancy/delivery are covered at 30%.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        Japan's work visa system rewards professionals with relevant qualifications and offers genuine pathways to long-term residence. The HSP points system accelerates permanent residence to 1-3 years for high scorers, making it one of the faster PR tracks in developed countries.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        Healthcare through Shakai Hoken is excellent and affordable. The 30% copay system, combined with monthly caps on out-of-pocket expenses, means even major medical events won't bankrupt you. Most expats add modest supplemental insurance for enhanced coverage but find the base system more than adequate.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The main challenge is the degree-job match requirement, which can block otherwise qualified candidates. Work culture can also be demanding, though this is improving—especially in international companies and tech startups. Learning Japanese, while not visa-required, dramatically improves both career prospects and daily life.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Bottom Line</h3>
        <p class="text-primary-800">Japan's work visa offers excellent healthcare coverage, a clear path to PR (especially with HSP), and access to one of the world's most fascinating cultures. The degree-job match requirement is strict, so verify eligibility before committing to a move. Shakai Hoken provides comprehensive coverage at 30% copay—supplemental insurance is optional but inexpensive for peace of mind.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

